  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the good game stalls ideas that which gives much money than others at college fests?",
  "response": "College fests are great opportunities for student organizations and vendors to set up game stalls that can attract a lot of participants and generate income. Here are some profitable game stall ideas that can draw in crowds and potentially provide a good return on investment:\n\n1. **Carnival Games**: Classic carnival games like ring toss, balloon darts, or bean bag toss are always popular. Charge a small fee per game, and offer prizes for winners to attract more players.\n\n2. **Photo Booth with Props**: Set up a themed photo booth with fun props and backdrops. Charge a fee for people to take pictures, or offer a package deal for multiple shots.\n\n3. **Mystery Box**: Set up a game where participants pay a fee to select a mystery box containing random prizes. You can have a mix of low-value items and one or two high-value items to increase excitement.\n\n4. **Escape Room Challenge**: Create a mini escape room experience with puzzles and clues. Participants pay to enter and compete against the clock to solve the puzzles.\n\n5. **Spin the Wheel**: Set up a colorful wheel with various prizes. Participants can pay to spin the wheel for a chance to win different items or discounts.\n\n6. **Dart Throw**: Set up a dartboard game where participants can pay to throw darts at balloons or targets for prizes.\n\n7. **Karaoke Challenge**: Organize a karaoke competition where participants pay to sing their favorite songs. Offer small prizes for the best performances or audience applause.\n\n8. **Cup Stacking Contest**: Have a speed cup stacking contest where participants pay to enter. Offer prizes for the fastest times.\n\n9. **Balloon Pop**: Fill balloons with various prizes and hang them on a board. Participants pay to pop a balloon and win whatever's inside.\n\n10. **Fortune Teller**: Hire a fortune teller or create a mystical space where participants can pay for a tarot card reading or palm reading.\n\n11. **Virtual Reality Experiences**: If you have access to VR equipment, set up a VR station where participants can pay to experience different games or simulations.\n\n12. **Trivia/Game Show**: Host a trivia game or game show format challenge where participants can pay to compete for prizes. Use popular culture, college-related questions, or fun general knowledge themes.\n\n13. **Challenge the Professor/Faculty**: Set up a game where students can challenge professors or faculty members to a fun competition (like trivia, video games, or sports) for a fee.\n\n14. **DIY Craft Corner**: Allow participants to create their own crafts for a fee, like custom t-shirts, friendship bracelets, or painting. \n\n15. **Food Challenges**: Host fun food challenges, such as spicy food eating contests or cupcake decorating contests, where participants pay an entry fee and have the chance to win prizes.\n\nWhen planning your game stall, ensure it\u2019s engaging, fun, and accessible, with clear rules and reasonable pricing. Marketing your stall effectively through social media and word-of-mouth can also help attract more participants.",
